# Project Structure & Architecture

## 1. Application Paradigm
This is a local Web Application built with Streamlit, NOT a command-line interface (CLI) tool. The user interacts exclusively through the browser via file upload widgets (drag-and-drop).

## 2. Directory & File Tree
The project MUST strictly adhere to this structure:
* `app.py` -> The Streamlit frontend and main entry point. Handles UI, file uploads, and displaying the final table.
* `src/` -> Folder containing all business logic.
  * `__init__.py`
  * `parser.py` -> Phase 1 logic. SOH ingestion, bucketing, rollup computation, and inventory orchestration.
  * `orders.py` -> Phase 2 logic. Abaserve orders file parsing, customer-tier deductions, Pistola/FQ-SO fallback.
* `Groups.csv` -> The static Alias Mapping file (lives in the root, never uploaded by the user).
* `requirements.txt` -> Project dependencies.
* `run.bat` -> Windows batch file to easily launch the Streamlit app.
* `run.command` -> Mac/Linux bash script to easily launch the Streamlit app.
* `.cursor/rules/phase2.mdc` -> Phase 2 specification (orders format, deduction rules).
* `tests/fixtures/` -> (optional) Sample orders files for unit tests (`orders_sample.xls`, `orders_minimal.xls`).

## 3. Dependencies
The `requirements.txt` must include:
* `streamlit` (For the web UI)
* `pandas` (For data manipulation)
* `openpyxl` (For reading .xlsx files, if needed)
* `xlrd` (For reading older .xls SOH and Order files)

## 4. Separation of Concerns
* `app.py` MUST NOT contain raw data parsing, bucketing math, or mapping logic. It only handles Streamlit widgets and rendering.
* `src/parser.py` MUST NOT contain any Streamlit code (`st.`). It takes raw pandas dataframes, processes them, and returns standard Python dictionaries/dataframes.
* `src/orders.py` MUST NOT contain any Streamlit code (`st.`). See `phase2.mdc` for the full specification.